In Java, variables are containers used to store data in memory. Variables define how data is stored, accessed, and manipulated.

A variable in Java has three components,
a. Data Type: Defines the kind of data stored (e.g., int, String, float).
b. Variable Name: A unique identifier following Java naming rules.
c. Value: The actual data assigned to the variable.

class Geeks {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        
        // Declaring and initializing variables
        
        // Integer variable  
        int age = 25;       
        
        // String variable  
        String name = "GeeksforGeeks"; 
        
        // Double variable 
        double salary = 50000.50;     
​
        // Displaying the values of variables
        System.out.println("Age: " + age);          
        System.out.println("Name: " + name);        
        System.out.println("Salary: " + salary);
    }
}

Output
Age: 25
Name: GeeksforGeeks
Salary: 50000.5

